## Issue 1: gs-3-4 — Cadd6 Embellishment (Going Gets Tough)

**Exercise ID:** `gs-3-4` (Level 3)  
**Title:** Song Study: Going Gets Tough  
**Problematic text:** `"The Cadd6 Embellishment: While holding a C chord, hammer your pinky onto the 2nd fret of the G string."`

**Why it's physically impractical:** In a standard open C chord (x32010), the **middle finger** is already on the D string 2nd fret, and the **ring finger** is on the A string 3rd fret. The G string is already **open** in a C chord. Hammering the pinky onto the G string 2nd fret is physically possible, but calling the result "Cadd6" is misleading — fretting the G string at fret 2 produces an A note, which would make this a C(add6) or Cadd6 (C-E-G-A). However, the bigger issue is that the instruction says "hammer your pinky onto the 2nd fret of the G string" when **holding a C chord shape**. The standard C chord voicing has no finger on the G string (it's open), so the G string is available for the pinky. This is physically **doable** but **awkward** because the pinky has to reach from behind the ring finger (which is on A string fret 3) down to the G string fret 2 — a backwards reach. The pinky would need to curl under the ring finger's position, which is a stretch for beginners at Level 3.

**What would actually work:** "While holding a C chord, hammer your pinky onto the **3rd fret** of the G string (Bb). Then pull off back to the open G." Or alternatively, describe the embellishment more accurately: "Lift your middle finger off the D string briefly to hammer-on from open D to fret 2 (E), creating a melodic wobble within the C chord." This matches common C chord embellishments guitarists actually use. If the Cadd6 (A note on G string) is truly the intended sound, the instruction should note that the pinky reaches to the G string fret 2 from below the ring finger — this is a stretch that should be warned about.

---

## Issue 2: gs-1-9 — Bending on B string fret 8

**Exercise ID:** `gs-1-9` (Level 1)  
**Title:** Bending & Vibrato — Making the Guitar Sing  
**Problematic text:** `"Place your ring finger on the B string, 8th fret (G note). Now push the string upward (toward the ceiling)... The pitch should rise. Push until it sounds like the note at the 9th fret (Ab)."`

**Why this is a contextual concern (not a hard impossibility):** This exercise is in Level 1, which is positioned entirely around open chords (frets 0-3) and the Am pentatonic at frets 5-8. The student is asked to bend at fret 8 on the B string. This is physically fine — fret 8 has reasonable tension and the B string bends easily. However, the exercise title and context suggest this is being done within the Am pentatonic shape (position 1, frets 5-8). The text is self-consistent here. **No actual issue** — this one checks out. The student is working in the pentatonic box, not holding open chords simultaneously.

---

## Issue 3: gs-2-7 — Bending at fret 7 on the G string

**Exercise ID:** `gs-2-7` (Level 2)  
**Title:** Bending — Making the Guitar Sing  
**Problematic text:** `"Half-step bend prep: play the note at fret 7 on the G string (D). Now play fret 8 (Eb — the blue note). Listen to the distance between them — that's a half step. Now go back to fret 7 and BEND the string upward (toward the ceiling) until it matches the pitch of fret 8."`

Then later: `"Full-step bend: play fret 7 (D), then play fret 9 (E). That's a whole step — twice as far. Now bend from fret 7 to match fret 9."`

**Physical assessment:** Bending the G string at fret 7 is reasonable for a half-step bend. A **whole-step bend on the G string at fret 7** is more demanding — the G string is one of the wound strings (on most acoustic/electric sets it's the thinnest wound or a plain string depending on gauge), and fret 7 is mid-neck where tension is moderate. For a Level 2 student, a whole-step bend on the G string at fret 7 is challenging but not impossible. The exercise correctly emphasizes supporting fingers. **No actual issue** — this is physically demanding but appropriate with the supporting finger technique described.

---

## Issue 4: gs-4-4b — Jah Werx Barre Chords at Level 4

**Exercise ID:** `gs-4-4b` (Level 4)  
**Title:** Song Study: Jah Werx — Susto (B-F#-E)  
**Problematic text:** `"B is x24442 (A-shape barre at fret 2). F# is 244322 (E-shape barre at fret 2)."`

**Why this is a positioning concern:** This exercise appears in Level 4 (The Offbeat), but barre chords are not formally taught until Level 5 (Barre Chord World). The exercise acknowledges this indirectly by offering B7 (x21202) as a substitute, but it still teaches full barre shapes. This is a **curriculum sequencing issue** rather than a physical impossibility — the student is asked to do something they haven't been taught yet. The Sarah note even says "this exercise is your bridge between open-chord reggae and barre-heavy reggae-rock of Level 7" — acknowledging it's ahead of its level. **Not a mechanical issue per se, but worth noting.**

---

## Issue 5: gs-6-6 — Friends (levitation room) riff at frets 5-7

**Exercise ID:** `gs-6-6` (Level 6)  
**Title:** Song Study: Friends (levitation room)  
**Problematic text:** `"hold the Em shape as a foundation, then use hammer-ons and pull-offs on the G, B, and high E strings around frets 5-7. The riff outlines the Em chord melodically... Then slide your hand down into the Dmaj7 shape at the 5th fret"`

**Why this is a positional conflict:** The student is told to hold an Em chord shape (022000 — open position, frets 0-2) as a "foundation" while performing hammer-ons and pull-offs at frets 5-7. You **cannot** hold an open Em chord (frets 0-2) and simultaneously play hammer-ons at fret 5-7. Your hand has to leave the Em position entirely to reach frets 5-7. The instruction to "hold the chord shape as a foundation" is misleading — in reality, the guitarist would be playing an Em-derived shape or fragment higher up the neck, not the open Em. Then "slide your hand down into the Dmaj7 shape at the 5th fret" — but the open Dmaj7 (xx0220) is at frets 0-2, not fret 5. There's a contradiction between the open chord voicings defined earlier in the level and the fret positions described for the riff.

**What would actually work:** Clarify that the riff uses an Em **barre shape** or partial shape at the 7th fret area (e.g., Em rooted at fret 7 on the A string), not the open Em chord. Or describe it as: "Play single notes and double-stops on the G, B, and high E strings around frets 5-7 that outline the Em tonality — you are NOT holding the open Em shape during this. Your hand is up at the 5th-7th fret area." The Dmaj7 "at the 5th fret" should be clarified as a partial voicing or fragment at that position, not the open Dmaj7 shape.

---

## Issue 6: gs-3-4 — Going Gets Tough bass-strum pattern

**Exercise ID:** `gs-3-4` (Level 3)  
**Title:** Song Study: Going Gets Tough  
**Problematic text:** `"Play the LOW root note of each chord on the downbeat (low E string 3rd fret for G, A string 3rd fret for C), then a quick, snappy strum of the upper strings on the upbeat."`

**Physical assessment:** With a capo on fret 1, playing "G shape" means the actual chord is Ab. "Low E string 3rd fret for G" means fret 3 relative to the capo (actual fret 4), which is the root G#/Ab. "A string 3rd fret for C" means fret 3 relative to the capo (actual fret 4), which is C#/Db. The fret numbers refer to the shapes (as if the capo were the nut), which is standard practice. The bass-strum alternation is physically fine — pick the bass note, then strum the treble strings. **No actual issue** — this is standard alternating-bass technique and correctly described.

---

## Issue 7: gs-1-3 — Am chord voicing has ring finger on wrong string

**Exercise ID:** `gs-1-3` (Level 1)  
**Title:** Open Chords — Am, C, G, D, Em  
**Problematic text:** `"Am: index finger on B string fret 1, middle finger on D string fret 2, ring finger on G string fret 2."`

**Physical assessment:** Standard Am is x02210: index on B string fret 1, middle on D string fret 2, ring on G string fret 2. This is correct. **No issue.**

---

## Summary of Genuine Mechanical Issues Found

### ISSUE 1 (Medium): gs-3-4 — Cadd6 Embellishment Awkwardness
**File:** `level-03-power-and-drive.js`, line ~107  
The pinky hammer-on to G string fret 2 while holding a C chord is an awkward backwards reach for a Level 3 student. The pinky has to reach below/behind the ring finger (which is on A string fret 3). Not impossible for experienced players, but poorly described for this skill level. The text should either describe the finger choreography more carefully or suggest a more accessible embellishment.

### ISSUE 2 (High): gs-6-6 — Friends Riff Position Conflict
**File:** `level-06-jangle-and-shimmer.js`, line ~154  
The exercise tells students to "hold the Em shape as a foundation" while playing hammer-ons at frets 5-7. Open Em lives at frets 0-2 — you cannot hold it and play at frets 5-7 simultaneously. Similarly, "Dmaj7 shape at the 5th fret" contradicts the open Dmaj7 (xx0220) taught earlier in the level. The riff description conflates open chord shapes with positional playing higher on the neck. This needs to be rewritten to either describe the actual hand position used (partial shapes/fragments at fret 5-7) or acknowledge the hand leaves the open chord position.

---

### Issues NOT Found (Good News)

The following categories were checked and no problems were found:

- **Wrong hand for technique**: All bending, palm muting, and strumming instructions correctly identify the picking/strumming hand vs. fretting hand.
- **Bending at impractical frets**: No instructions to bend at fret 1 or to bend the low E string. All bending happens at frets 7-8 on the G and B strings, which is standard.
- **Techniques that don't match the song**: Song studies generally match the Gemini analysis. Dope & Smoke is correctly described as staccato/choppy strumming. Going Gets Tough correctly uses the boom-chuck pattern. The Stormtrooper riff correctly uses power chords with the skank switch.
- **Fret references contradicting chord positions**: All pentatonic exercises correctly place the student in the frets 5-8 zone away from open chord work. The exercises that use open chords don't simultaneously ask for high-fret work (except the Friends issue above).
- **Impossible simultaneous actions**: No instructions ask a finger to be in two places at once (except the edge case of the Friends riff in gs-6-6).
- **Position jumps while holding chords**: The curriculum properly separates chord strumming exercises from single-note pentatonic work. Students aren't asked to hold an open chord while playing at fret 12.</result>
